## Required TypeScript Rules

- `"strict": true` in `tsconfig.json` — **non-negotiable**, enforce in every project
- All event handlers typed: `React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>`, `React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>`
- All API response shapes in `src/types/api.ts` as TypeScript interfaces
- Zod schemas for all form validation and all API response validation at the boundary

---

## Required Test Coverage

| Subject | Test Tool | Minimum |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Custom hooks | `renderHook` (RTL) | All return values + state transitions |
| Shared components | React Testing Library | Renders, interactions, a11y |
| API functions | MSW handlers in `src/mocks/handlers.ts` | Happy + error paths |
| Critical user flows | Playwright E2E | At least one E2E per flow |

---

## Violations

### ❌ Violation 1 — Feature hook contains raw fetch call

**Trigger:** Agent generates `useOrderHistory` that calls `fetch('/api/orders')` directly.

**What to flag:**
> All server communication goes through the `api/` layer. Create
> `src/api/orders.ts` with `getOrderHistory(): Promise<Order[]>`, then
> reference it in the React Query hook. The component and the hook never
> contain fetch/axios calls directly.

---

### ❌ Violation 2 — `useEffect` with exhaustive-deps ESLint disable

**Trigger:** PR adds `// eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps`
above a `useEffect` with an empty dependency array.

**What to flag:**
> Suppressing the exhaustive-deps rule here means `userId` in the closure
> will go stale when the prop changes — this is a latent bug. Either include
> `userId` in the dependency array, or if the intent is truly "run only on
> mount," replace with a `useRef` pattern or move the logic to an event
> handler that fires explicitly. Never suppress this lint rule.
